---
import GuideLayout from '../../layouts/GuideLayout.astro';
import { pmt, amortizeLoan } from '../../lib/loan.js';

const fmt = (n: number) => '$' + Math.round(n).toLocaleString('en-US');
const LOAN = 300000;
const R15 = 5.9, R30 = 6.5;
const p15 = pmt(LOAN, R15, 180), p30 = pmt(LOAN, R30, 360);
const a15 = amortizeLoan({ principal: LOAN, annualRate: R15, payment: p15 });
const a30 = amortizeLoan({ principal: LOAN, annualRate: R30, payment: p30 });
const b5_15 = a15.rows[59].balance, b5_30 = a30.rows[59].balance;
// 30yr paid like 15: extra = p15 - p30
const hybrid = amortizeLoan({ principal: LOAN, annualRate: R30, payment: p30, extraMonthly: p15 - p30 });
---

<GuideLayout
  title="15 vs. 30-Year Mortgage: The Real Math (Including the Third Option)"
  metaTitle="15 vs 30 Year Mortgage — Real Cost Comparison | Payoff Logic"
  description="A $300k loan compared honestly: 15-year vs 30-year payments, total interest, 5-year equity — plus the '30 paid like a 15' strategy and exactly what it costs vs the real 15."
  slug="15-vs-30-year-mortgage"
  updated="July 11, 2026"
  updatedISO="2026-07-11"
  kind="race"
  tool={{ href: '/15-year-mortgage-calculator/', label: '15-vs-30 comparison calculator' }}
>
  <div class="answer">
    <strong>Direct answer:</strong> On a {fmt(LOAN)} loan (15-yr at {R15}%, 30-yr at
    {R30}% — shorter terms price lower), the 15-year costs {fmt(p15 - p30)} more per
    month but saves <strong>{fmt(a30.totalInterest - a15.totalInterest)}</strong> in
    total interest and builds equity roughly 3× faster in the first five years. The
    30-year's advantage is flexibility: a lower <em>required</em> payment you can
    voluntarily exceed.
  </div>

  <h2>Side by side, no spin</h2>
  <div class="tablewrap"><table>
    <thead><tr><th></th><th class="num">15-year @ {R15}%</th><th class="num">30-year @ {R30}%</th></tr></thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td>Monthly payment (P&amp;I)</td><td class="num">{fmt(p15)}</td><td class="num">{fmt(p30)}</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Total interest</td><td class="num">{fmt(a15.totalInterest)}</td><td class="num">{fmt(a30.totalInterest)}</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Total paid</td><td class="num">{fmt(LOAN + a15.totalInterest)}</td><td class="num">{fmt(LOAN + a30.totalInterest)}</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Balance after 5 years</td><td class="num">{fmt(b5_15)}</td><td class="num">{fmt(b5_30)}</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Equity from payments, 5 yrs</td><td class="num">{fmt(LOAN - b5_15)}</td><td class="num">{fmt(LOAN - b5_30)}</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table></div>
  <p>
    Two structural reasons the 15-year wins on cost: less time borrowing, and a rate
    discount — lenders price 15-year money about half a point cheaper because it's
    less risky to them. That discount is real and only available by committing to the
    higher payment.
  </p>

  <h2>The third option: a 30 paid like a 15</h2>
  <p>
    Take the 30-year, then voluntarily pay the 15-year amount ({fmt(p15)}). On our
    numbers that pays off in about {Math.floor(hybrid.months / 12)} years
    {hybrid.months % 12} months with {fmt(hybrid.totalInterest)} of interest —
    <strong>{fmt(hybrid.totalInterest - a15.totalInterest)} more than the true
    15-year</strong>. That gap is precisely the price of flexibility: you're paying the
    30-year rate for an escape hatch you can use if income drops. Cheap insurance for
    some households, wasted money for others with rock-solid income.
  </p>

  <h2>Who should lean which way</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Lean 15-year:</strong> stable income, emergency fund intact, retirement match captured, and the higher payment still leaves savings room. The forced discipline plus the rate discount is the most efficient equity builder available to most households.</li>
    <li><strong>Lean 30-year:</strong> variable income, young kids/child-care years, other high-return uses for cash (employer match, expensive debt), or you're buying near your affordability ceiling. Add extras when you can — the <a href="/extra-payment-mortgage-calculator/">extra-payment calculator</a> shows each scenario.</li>
    <li><strong>Already own?</strong> Refinancing a 30 into a 15 mid-life is common once income grows — run the break-even in the <a href="/refinance-calculator/">refinance calculator</a>.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>The mistake to avoid</h2>
  <p>
    Don't take the 15-year payment if it crowds out your emergency fund — house-rich,
    cash-poor is fragile, and missed payments cost more than the interest savings.
    The <a href="/house-affordability-calculator/">affordability calculator</a> (set
    the term to 15) shows whether the shorter term fits your ratios before you fall in
    love with the savings number.
  </p>
</GuideLayout>
